{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504852"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:21:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:21:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2379"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2379"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.63,0.06,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90721"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2379"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74865"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3390"},{"type":"tags","id":"3460"},{"type":"tags","id":"4208"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1512"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36041"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90721"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two day history of worsening upper abdominal pain, with associated nausea and vomiting. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is a non-smoker. She drinks about three glasses of wine a week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she is in obvious distress and pain. Her blood pressure is 105/70mmHg, pulse 100/min, temperature 37.9\u2103, respiratory rate 18/min and SpO2 99% on room air. There is a visible yellow tinge to her sclera. On abdominal examination, her abdomen is not distended but there is tenderness in the right upper quadrant. There is no hepatosplenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer laboratory investigations are unremarkable apart from a raised white cell count, alkaline phosphatase and direct bilirubin. An abdominal ultrasound shows dilated intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts and multiple hyperechoic spheres within the gallbladder. Intravenous antibiotics and fluid resuscitation is started.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laparoscopic cholecystectomy","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)","Magnetic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)","Open cholecystectomy","Percutaneous cholecystostomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has cholangitis and is in danger of going into septic shock. She has presented with Charcot\u2019s triad - fever, jaundice and right upper quadrant pain. There is also leukocytosis and elevated markers of cholestasis i.e. raised ALP and direct bilirubin. Her ultrasound confirms the presence of gallstones and a dilated biliary system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe needs rapid intervention. If she did not have evidence of sepsis and haemodynamic instability, then \u003Cstrong\u003Emagnetic retrograde cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E (\u003Cstrong\u003EMRCP)\u003C/strong\u003E might be an appropriate initial investigation to get a clearer definition of the biliary tree. In this instance, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment of choice to decompress the biliary system. In mild cases that respond well to antibiotics, the majority of patients will undergo ERCP 24-48 hours electively after clinical improvement. In severe cases, such as here, ERCP should be performed immediately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E removes potential gallstones but does not necessarily remove gallstones in the common bile duct. Moreover, this procedure is risky in septic patients when less invasive means of achieving biliary drainage are available. Whilst an \u003Cstrong\u003Eopen cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E might give easier access to the biliary tree, an ERCP is a safer initial approach, with less morbidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous cholecystostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is an image-guided placement of drainage catheter into the gallbladder lumen, mainly for patients with acute cholecystitis for whom urgent surgery is not thought appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExtracorporeal shock wave lithotripsy is used to break down gallstones. It may be used as an elective procedure and commonly require multiple sessions. It is not the primary intervention, especially in an acutely unwell patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cholangitis requires prompt recognition of the underlying problem and, where indicated, prompt decompression of the biliary system."],"references":["Coelho-Prabhu N, Shah ND, Van Houten H, et al. Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography: utilisation and outcomes in a 10-year population-based cohort. BMJ Open 2013;3(5). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4387279/","Mosler P. Diagnosis and management of acute cholangitis. Curr Gastroenterol Rep 2011;13:166. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21207254/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74865"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2379"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74865"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T15:19:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-15T09:21:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2379"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90721"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},